         <abstract>
            <p>
               Rational approximants are defined from double power series in variables $x$ and $y$, and it is shown that these approximants have the following properties: (i) they possess symmetry between $x$ and $y$; (ii) they are in general unique; (iii) if $x = 0$ or $y = 0$, they reduce to diagonal Padé approximants; (iv) their definition is invariant under the group of transformations $x = Au/(1 - Bu), y = A\upsilon/(1 - C\upsilon)$ with $A \neq 0$; (v) an approximant formed from the reciprocal series is the reciprocal of the corresponding original approximant. Possible variations, extensions and generalisations of these results are discussed. 
            </p>
          </abstract>
